\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 3. Model-by-Model Breakdown\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Linear vs. Ridge Regression (The Tie):
\f0\b0  Ridge Regression (with an optimal penalty alpha of 1.0) and standard Linear Regression performed identically. Their $R^2$, MSE, and MAE are exactly the same up to the 5th decimal place. This indicates that your dataset did not suffer from severe "multicollinearity" (features confusing each other), meaning the Ridge penalty didn't have to do much work.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Lasso Regression (Slightly Lower):
\f0\b0  Lasso performed just slightly worse ($R^2$ of 0.6417). Because Lasso forces the coefficients of less important features completely to zero (effectively deleting them), it traded a tiny bit of accuracy for a simpler model.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Speed (Time):
\f0\b0  
\f1\b Linear Regression is the clear winner here.
\f0\b0  Because Ridge and Lasso had to run through GridSearchCV to test multiple alpha values across 5 different folds of data, they took significantly longer (1.69s and 0.83s) compared to the standard Linear Regression (0.17s), which just solved the math instantly.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Summary / Next Steps\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 The Winner: Standard Linear Regression.
\f0\b0 \
Because the advanced regularized models (Ridge and Lasso) did not provide any boost to accuracy, the standard Linear Regression is the best choice for this specific pipeline because it is mathematically simpler and 
\f1\b 10x faster
\f0\b0  to compute.\

\f1\b How to improve the 64% accuracy:
\f0\b0 \
Since linear models seem to have hit a ceiling at 64%, car prices likely have complex, non-linear relationships that straight lines can't capture. If your computer has the memory, you could try bringing back 
\f1\b Polynomial Features
\f0\b0  (with a smaller subset of columns) or moving to a tree-based model like 
\f1\b Random Forest
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b XGBoost
\f0\b0 , which naturally handle complex car pricing logic much better than linear regression!\
